40abb4f7d73ceadf087e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c41ab4521c4c2b6bde7b03ec4d9531acdc101f7e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a545f286136f5024bdadaa47d305e437cf32614f.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" users to select and view details about assigned tasks.\n\n\n  \n After selecting tasks and clicking the  Next  button, the workflow finishes and the selected tasks are assigned to you. \n   Troubleshooting \n If your workflow does not work as expected, run the workflow trace as described in this  article , identify the problem, fix it, restart the server, and run the workflow again. \n When needed, you can also consult the documentation for  sequential workflows  and  XSL Transformations . \n For more complex workflows, you can also use the data flow view, which you can access by selecting  Show data flow  over the context store: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/2e285259f66e0e3184f1d8efd4c89d3947bb0a8e.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a data processing flowchart illustrating three main tasks: \u002201_LoadData_Task,\u0022 \u002202_Transform_Task,\u0022 and \u002203_StoreData_Task.\u0022 The flow begins at a green \u0022Start\u0022 node and concludes at a red \u0022End\u0022 node. Arrows indicate the data flow between tasks, with blue and red colors highlighting different paths. The \u002202_Transform_Task\u0022 includes components like \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022Task,\u0022 \u0022Parameters,\u0022 and \u0022XslScript.\u0022 A menu is displayed for the \u0022Task\u0022 node with options including \u0022Delete,\u0022 \u0022Hide data flow,\u0022 \u0022Show data flow,\u0022 and \u0022Actions.\u0022 This representation is designed for managing and visualizing data processing sequences.\n\n\n  \n Here you can see the data flow between individual context stores and the workflow steps where a given context store is used, which can help you identify the source of potential issues. \n   More workflow examples \n More examples of various sequential workflows can be found in the posts below this text. \n    EXAMPLE 1: Workflow using parameter and updating value via XPath  \n    EXAMPLE 2: Workflow with for-each loop and call of another workflow  \n\n---\n\n@vikter (2026-03-25 10:24:02Z):\n   More examples of using sequential workflows \n   EXAMPLE 1: Workflow using parameter and updating value via XPath \n This workflow works with a particular data record only \u2013 the record active in both the grid or form view in the client application.  The Id of this record is passed, for example, as a parameter from the UI action that triggers this workflow. \n   Data type based context store \n To do this we need to get the record\u2019s Id in the load step using an  UI action parameter  and then store it in an extra context store based on a simple data type suitable for storing object Ids ( Uniqueidentifier ) instead of data structure: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/aca0354da823cff10355cc4d647b6192f66863c3.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a context store labeled \u0022IN_TaskId.\u0022 It contains details organized into two main sections: (Info) and (Misc). The (Info) section includes schema item attributes with fields for \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable,\u0022 and \u0022Name,\u0022 indicating the name is \u0022IN_TaskId.\u0022 The (Misc) section presents additional properties, showing \u0022DataType\u0022 set to \u0022UniqueIdentifier,\u0022 with other fields listed as \u0022DefaultSet,\u0022 \u0022DisableConstraints,\u0022 \u0022IsReturnValue,\u0022 \u0022RuleSet,\u0022 and \u0022Structure,\u0022 all providing specific configurations with corresponding boolean values. The interface appears to be part of a data management or schema configuration tool.\n\n\n  \n Note: The prefix \u201CIN_\u201D in the context store name is used for INput parameter values. \n   Workflow parameter \n Now we need to create a new parameter (context store reference) and bind it with that context store containing the Id of the record we want to work with: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8b140df982f17d6075da296a3512d16fb9ac67dc.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface for a \u0022Context Store Reference\u0022 configuration, specifically for \u0022Task_parId.\u0022 The visible elements include a header indicating the reference type, followed by a detailed breakdown under two sections: (Schema Item) and Misc. The Schema Item section includes fields labeled \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable,\u0022 and \u0022Name,\u0022 with values False and Task_parId. In the Misc section, there are fields for \u0022CastToDataType\u0022 set to String, \u0022ContextStore\u0022 assigned to IN_TaskId, and \u0022XPath\u0022 indicated as /. The purpose of this interface appears to be for configuring and managing context store references within a data handling system.\n\n\n","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-02T00:02:37"},"vector":[-0.016864823,-0.00772666,-0.08146083,0.029943455,0.008197488,0.004090045,0.006904186,0.024628235,0.0037588216,0.011884696,0.025645804,-0.022092272,0.0229213,0.032593332,0.038489897,-0.0017038003,-0.023953386,0.009662662,0.0021734934,0.0199843,0.013355838,0.007460282,0.042202316,0.03630306,0.008224521,0.04785911,-0.012669625,-0.032407936,-0.001946279,0.027916992,-0.011228172,-0.038215663,0.01521813,-0.01957375,-0.023882495,-0.0058025783,-0.01680011,7.750596E-05,-0.0461131,0.021310171,0.008701195,-0.005227441,-0.0025389239,0.01081063,0.02258423,-0.038917772,-0.003910439,-0.018569164,-0.011728767,-0.058788106,-0.063371256,-0.020604642,0.023671463,-0.06101639,0.047425687,0.012107944,-0.06638573,-0.0013437917,-0.06576098,0.012376341,-0.0063964664,-0.0024758044,0.012235359